Restoring the very American ideal that labour rights are also human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a bill to protect union organization as a civil right.
“The way unions work is the way middle-class jobs work,” says Ellison, a Democratic senator in Minnesota who is co-chair of the Congressional Committee.
That's why I'm so proud to present, along with John Lewis's model of occasional rights, a law that empowers employees.
This breakthrough legislation will give workers the same legal options to prevent discrimination in organizing unions as in other forms of discrimination - and stop anti-union forces
Adjusting the Labour Relations Act to allow all employees who face discrimination, if they want to join a trade union, to go to civil court - and to sue for compensation or damages - is the right and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and other lawmakers are proposing is to re-establish the American ideal.
Despite the trade union struggles that have taken place in recent years – in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states – Americans once encouraged countries around the world to adopt, expand, and respect labor rights.
There were times, and millions of Americans still remember them, when the country promoted democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to assembly in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers encouraged the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the military autocracy of Hideki Toja would be replaced by democracy.
They were convinced that employees and their unions played a role in shaping the new Japan, included language in them, and openly acknowledged that “the right of employees to assemble, collectively negotiate, and act is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers encouraged the Germans to create a constitution that would ensure Adolf Hitler’s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Realizing that workers would need to organize and promote themselves in the new nation, the Germans included a clause that openly states: “The right to form associations that will secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and to every profession or profession.
Agreements that limit this right or seek to infringe it will be terminated. Measures leading to the fulfillment of such purpose are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a universal treaty, it included the petitioners and Roosevelt’s guarantee that “everyone has the right to form and join trade unions to protect their interests.”
For generations, Americans have embraced the basic premise that labour rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries how to create a civil and democratic society, Americans explained that the right to form labor unions – and their participation in collective bargaining with companies and government agencies as equal partners – must be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is definitely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and promote themselves in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said 50 years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today everyone knows that the trade unions have not diminished the power of the nation, but have expanded it.
They have raised the standard of living of millions of people, created a market for industry and raised production to an unimaginable level.
Those who attack the trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History does not forget, and neither should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination in the organisation of trade unions - has been very delayed.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that elevated America and made it a real promise of democracy.
A judge has temporarily blocked a law that could shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana.
A federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked a Louisiana law that lawyers say would likely close all five abortion clinics in the state.
A decree enacted by Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal in June, due to enter into force on September 1, would require abortion doctors to have the right to receive a patient in a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
The judge's order means that doctors can continue to perform legal abortions temporarily and must obtain this permit in the meantime.
"The nominating party will be able to legally conduct its business and in the meantime obtain permission," federal judge John deGravelles said in a ruling.
The hearing will be scheduled within one month so that the judge can issue a more permanent order on the law.
Abortion rights activists welcomed the resolution, which is the latest in a series of similar measures, and said it would give doctors more time to get permission.
“Today’s decision ensures that women in Louisiana are safe from a devious law designed to deprive them of their health and rights,” Nancy Northup, president and executive director of the Center for Reproductive Rights, said in a statement.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision also applies to doctors from two clinics that were not among the plaintiffs, and they are also requesting this permission.
Louisiana is among the eleven states that have enacted similar laws, with courts in Alabama and Mississippi declaring such measures unconstitutional by provision.
Key parts of the Texas law that would shut down most of the state's remaining clinics were blocked by federal judges on Friday.
Women’s abortion rights activists, along with the Association of American Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, argue that the need to have such a permit places requirements on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion have argued that the measures are aimed at protecting women’s health, and some have also welcomed the fact that the clinics would be closed due to the measures.
The Center for Reproductive Rights said only one abortion doctor in Louisiana is licensed.
If all doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would also stop performing the procedure out of fear for his safety, the group said.
In response, Louisiana authorities said they would not penalize doctors who perform abortions while they wait for a rights request to be processed.
