Prison guards organize protests in Bulgaria
Hundreds of prison officials across Bulgaria took part in a nationwide protest rally in front of the Ministry of Justice in the capital Sofia.
At a peaceful demonstration, they reiterated their demand for the reintroduction of the original working conditions, which had recently changed.
In the list of requirements to be discussed with the interim Minister of justice Hristo Ivanov, there are also higher salaries.
For a month, the guards symbolically protested against the new working hours and demanded a return to the original twenty-four-hour shifts.
Although the unions of prison guards and representatives of the Ministry of Justice met, they did not agree, the Bulgarian State Radio (BNR) reported.
"The negotiations are still ongoing," Rosen Zhelyazkov, head of the General Directorate of the Prison Service, told BNR.
Members of the Federation of Workers' Trade Unions at the Ministry of the Interior are also expected to join the protests.
Why the Universe May Have More Dimensions and We Can't See Them
Physicists don’t usually write bestsellers, but Columbia University’s Brian Greene scored in 1999.
His book The Elegant Universe has become the most accessible way for the layman to penetrate the thicket of problems that many theoretical physicists deal with today - an attempt to unite two wonderfully working but mutually incompatible discoveries of the 20th century: quantum theory and the theory of general relativity.
One of the reasons for the success of the Elegant Universe is undoubtedly that the search for a unified physical theory is not a boring story.
Physicists have solved the fundamental problem between the two key theories (after all, at the moment our universe is de facto divided into two worlds with different laws) and solve it so imaginatively that it is worth retelling even to the layman.
Moreover, Greene dealt with the complex material so freshly and engagingly that he could not be blamed for how much interesting he did not include in his book.
In addition, he corrected his "mistake" for the most part in the next two books: The Structure of the Universe and Hidden Reality.
Apparently, even the author would not object if his book became obsolete faster, but the fact is that even after 15 years, the Elegant Universe still provides almost everything essential that an informed layman with an ambition to understand the world should know about this important part of theoretical physics.
It is quite likely that in the coming years it will be a bit more lively in this area (for example, because the LHC accelerator will finally go on "full gas"), so it is a good time to enter the Greenem nonviolent open doors of the world of modern physics.
How big can our universe be?
The idea that our universe may have more than three spatial dimensions can certainly sound silly, fantastic, strange or mystical.
Nevertheless, it is concrete and completely acceptable.
To understand this, let us turn our eyes for a moment from the universe as a whole to something more mundane, namely a long and thin garden hose for watering.
Imagine pulling a 100-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and watching the whole scene from a half-kilometre away (as in the picture and on the next page).
From such a distance, you can easily see a long hose stretched horizontally, but if you do not suffer from acuity, the thickness of the hose is difficult to recognize.
Given its great distance from the hose, you would think that an ant forced to live on a hose has only one dimension in which it can walk: the left-right dimension along the hose.
When someone asks you where the ant was at that moment, you only answer with one data: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we're saying is that from a half-kilometre away, a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, the hose is thick.
If we enlarge everything, we suddenly see a second dimension - in the shape of a circle wrapping the hose.
In such an enlarged view, it is obvious that the ant can actually move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the "dimension in/against the movement of the clockwise direction", i.e. around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You begin to understand that to determine the position of a small ant you need to enter two numbers: how far it is from the end of the hose and where there is a wrapping hose on the circle.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional (note Experts note that this chapter focuses purely on fault string theory.
Chapters 12 and 13 discuss non-disruptive aspects.).
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long longitudinal dimension is represented by a straight arrow, the dimension in the direction of the perimeter, indicated by a circular arrow, is short and bent.
However, there is a clear difference between these two dimensions.
The dimension along the hose is long and easily visible.
The dimension of the wrapping circuit of the hose is short, "coiled" and less noticeable.
In order to realize the existence of the circular dimension, we had to examine the hose with a significantly better resolution.
This example illustrates an important property of spatial dimensions.
The fact that they are divided into two groups.
They can be either large, large, and therefore directly visible, or, on the contrary, small, curled and much harder to observe.
Of course, in the above case, we did not exactly go through to reveal the "coiled" dimension enveloping the thickness of the hose.
You just had to bring a telescope to help.
But if the hose were thinner - like a hair or a capillary - the bent dimension would only be revealed with great effort.
In 1919, Kaluza sent Einstein an article in which he suggested that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than three dimensions known to us all.
Kaluza argued that the additional dimension provides an elegant and convincing framework in which Einstein's general relativity and Maxwell's electromagnetic theory can be weaved into a single, unified conceptual structure.
Immediately the question arises as to how this observation of Kaluza goes along with the obvious fact that we see three dimensions of space.
The answer, which Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines and which was clearly expressed and refined by the Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands and falls with the assertion that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and coiled dimensions.
This means that just like the dimensions in the hose-length direction, our universe has three dimensions that are large, vast and easily visible, and we are aware of their existence at every moment.
But by analogy with the circular circumference of a garden hose, the universe may have additional dimensions, tightly folded into space so tiny that they have remained hidden from our most advanced experimental apparatus.
In order to get a clearer idea of the essence of Kaluz's remarkable design, let's stay a little longer with the hose.
Imagine that we draw a fairly dense series of circles on the perimeter of the hose in black.
From a distance, the hose still looks like a thin one-dimensional line.
With the telescope, the drawing will now reveal the curved dimension even more easily, because we will see the motif from Figure 2.
We clearly see that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional, with one dimension large and almost unlimited, and with the other short and circular.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that our universe has a similar structure, but apart from one small circular dimension, it has three large spatial dimensions, that is, four spatial dimensions together.
It is difficult to draw an object with too many dimensions.
To help our imagination a little, note the illustration in Fig. 3; it shows two large dimensions and one small circular dimension.
In the picture, we enlarge the view of the geometry of the space similarly to how we enlarged the surface of the hose.
Each subsequent level represents a huge increase in the geometry of space from the previous level.
Our universe may have additional dimensions (we see them at the fourth magnification level) if they are folded into a sufficiently small space; this explains that we have not yet directly observed them.
The square grid represents the commonly known "big" dimensions, while the circles represent a new, tiny and twisted dimension.
Just like the loops of threads in a densely woven carpet, these circles exist in every place of usual dimensions - only for the sake of clarity we have drawn them only at the intersections in the square mesh.
The background of Figure 4 shows the commonly known structure of space - the ordinary world around us - in such common scales as meters, depicted by the side of a small square in a square grid.
In each following image, we will focus on a small area of the previous image; we will enlarge it to make it visible.
At first, nothing special happens, as we see in the first few levels of magnification.
However, as we go further on our journey to the microscopic properties of the geometry of space - to the fourth magnification level in Figure 3 - we suddenly see a new, curved dimension in the shape of a circle, similar to the loops of a thread in a densely woven piece of carpet.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that an additional circular dimension exists at every point in the direction of large dimensions, just as a hose has a circular circumference at every point of its length.
For the sake of clarity, we have drawn a circular dimension only in some, regularly spaced points.
Figure 4 summarizes Kaluz and Klein's idea of the microscopic structure of space geometry.
The similarity with the hose is obvious, although we note important differences.
First, the universe has three large, far-spreading spatial dimensions (of which we have drawn only two), while the hose has only one large dimension.
More importantly, we are now talking about the spatial geometry of the universe itself, not just some object inside the universe, like our hose.
But the basic idea is the same.
If the additional circularly curved dimension is extremely miniature, it is much harder to recognize it - as well as the circular circumference of the hose - than to observe the obvious, large and vast dimensions.
If the size of the extra dimension is small enough, it will actually reveal it beyond the power of our most modern magnifying tools.
Most importantly, however, the additional dimension is not just a round bump inside normal dimensions, as the two-dimensional illustration erroneously suggests.
A circular dimension is a new dimension that exists at every point of three ordinary large dimensions.
It is a dimension independent of the remaining three dimensions, just as the dimensions from top to bottom, from left to right and from front to back are independent (and perpendicular) of each other.
A sufficiently small ant could move in all four dimensions, and to determine its position we would need four data, in addition to the three usual still position in the circular dimension; if we count the time, then the data is five, in any case one more than we would normally expect.
