To our surprise, therefore, we find that even though we are aware of the existence of only three dimensions of space, Kaluz and Klein’s reasoning shows that this does not exclude the existence of additional coiled dimensions if they are small enough.
The universe may have more dimensions than we can see with the naked eye.
How small should they be?
The state-of-the-art technical equipment can recognize the structures of a large billionth of a billionth of a meter.
We can barely see the smaller curved dimensions.
In 1926, Klein combined Kaluz's original idea with several ideas from the emerging quantum mechanics.
His calculations suggested that the additional circular dimension could be about the same size as Planck's length, a size far beyond the resolution of today's instruments.
Since then, physicists have called the possibility of additional small spatial dimensions Kaluza-Klein theory.
