Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
A British woman describes how she thought she would die after being misdiagnosed for many years.
After being diagnosed with another disease, Karin Rodgers spent most of her adolescence thinking she had only a few years to live.
In fact, it was Charcot-Marie-Tooth Syndrome (CMT), a group of hereditary disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK said that poor diagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because very little is known about the disease.
It is estimated that approximately 23,000 people in the UK suffer from CMT, which can manifest symptoms in the area of motor skills such as muscle weakness, clumsy walking and twisted toes.
Patients may also experience numbness or pain, the condition is incurable and progressive, which means that the symptoms worsen over time.
When Rodgers was thirteen, she thought she was suffering from Freidreich's ataxia (FA), a disease with a very poor prognosis.
She believed that before her eighteenth birthday she would be confined to a wheelchair and dead before she was thirty.
A mother of two, now 51, says: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do the same things as the others.
I fell down every day and it took me longer.
I could never ride skates or skateboards with other kids, and I was bullied at school because of the way I walked and ran.”
When Rodgers was thirteen and had several surgeries to loosen her Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she took advantage of the fact that her doctor had left the room and looked into her file, where she learned that she was suffering from FA.
“I felt guilty because I was snooping, so I didn’t tell anyone, but when I got home, I looked up information about the disease in the library and wrote to the FA Association,” she says.
When they responded, I was in shock, completely panicked.
I thought I'd be in a wheelchair by the time I was eighteen, and I'd be dead by the time I was twenty-five, and in the meantime I'd gradually lose all my powers.
I was on my own, planning my own funeral.”
When she was seventeen, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she had anticipated, and she asked her surgeon.
He just stood up, hugged her, and said, "Honey, I don't think you have the disease, otherwise you'd be in a wheelchair.
I think it will be something much less life-threatening.”
After several genetic tests, he was found to have CMT.
"When he explained to me what CMT was, I thought I was a child of fortune," she said.
The charity CMT UK has launched the CMT Awareness Month to raise awareness of the disease.
Entrepreneurs in the Washington area: with the turn of the economy, taxes are rising
A growing economy means more customers, higher sales and new jobs.
And higher taxes, too.
According to a new survey published last week, state and local corporate taxation in the country rose slightly last year as the economy recovered faster, and Washington-based firms were no exception.
Businesses in Maryland and Virginia combined spent $27.6 billion in fiscal 2013 on state and local treasuries, an increase of 3.8% over the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The tax burden -- both state and local -- rose 4.3% last year to $671 billion, up from 3.9% last year, and was the third year in a row after 2009 and 2010, when taxes were reduced.
According to a study by Ernst & Young and the Center on State Taxation, state taxes increased by 4.3% faster than local levies by 3.9%.
More than half of the county's tax revenue, 56 percent, is from business tax, and 36 percent of Maryland's income is from companies.
Virginia, with 28%, has proportionally the smallest business tax revenue.
The researchers say the majority of tax revenue growth comes from an increase in the value of real estate owned by companies, which has increased real estate taxes by 3.7% this year for three consecutive years, with growth of -1%.
Although most of the profits come from big states like California, New York and Texas, it seems the same situation is in Washington.
Companies in D.C., Maryland and Virginia paid more than $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, an annual increase of 4.2% compared to $9.6 billion in 2012.
However, the apparent increase in property value does not so much drive up state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where property tax accounts for less than a fifth of corporate taxation.
For businesses in Virginia and D.C., property taxes account for nearly half of state and local taxes.
“In Maryland, they own a lot of real estate companies, most notably the D.C. tax base, the government, or non-profit organizations that don’t pay taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
So Maryland is forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, to pay for the same services that are in other states.
The recent increase in business tax revenue cannot be attributed only to the recovering real estate market.
According to the data, business revenues also appear to be increasing.
Companies in the region have published a corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, up from $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland levied $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the most in the region.
Although they are moving in the same direction, the local tax burden on entrepreneurs is not growing equally fast in these three places.
The growth rate in D.C. was at the national average level, at 4.3%, while Maryland’s growth was significantly higher, at 4.9%.
In Virginia alone, the tax increase was below average, to 4.1%.
Of the three counties (all of which have the same taxation), Virginia has the lowest corporate income tax rate, at 6%.
The Maryland corporate tax rate is 8.25%, while the D.C. average remains relatively high, at 9.975%.
A similar study conducted by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce this year showed that Virginia has lower state and local taxes and an overall more favorable tax climate than Maryland.
The D.C. study was not evaluated.
Despite this advantage, Virginia faces the pressure of competition from the south.
North Carolina recently signed a law lowering the corporate tax from 6.9% to 6%, just like Virginia, and next year the tax will be reduced to 5%.
If the state continues to meet its income targets in the coming year, the statutory income tax rate could be reduced to up to 3% in 2017.
According to a recent study, small businesses in Washington are doing better and therefore pay higher state and local taxes.
The business tax paid by small businesses as a personal income tax – a structure to offset rising costs by raising prices under which most companies are organized – in D.C., Maryland and Virginia rose by 20% last year to $2.4 billion, much faster than other taxes.
The researchers say the trend and nationwide trade tax increases are likely to continue next year, with total sales tax revenues for state and local governments rising to 6.2% compared to the same period last year in the first three quarters of 2014.
But Washington may be lagging behind, as cutting government spending takes its toll on the labor market.
